WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
[Unknown]: IVM.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:51.560
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the Scene and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:00:51.560 --> 00:00:52.560
[Unknown]: science.

00:00:52.560 --> 00:00:56.360
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Bhadma.

00:00:56.360 --> 00:01:00.900
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the Scene and the Unseen, my guest in this episode is the economist Tyler Carvin.

00:01:00.900 --> 00:01:05.200
[Amit Varma]: Though describing him as an economist seems inadequate, Tyler is a polymath who blogs

00:01:05.200 --> 00:01:09.100
[Amit Varma]: at Marginal Revolution, which is by far my favorite blog in the world, and he's written

00:01:09.100 --> 00:01:11.600
[Amit Varma]: numerous books on a variety of subjects.

00:01:11.600 --> 00:01:17.040
[Amit Varma]: He also runs a Marginal Revolution University, MRU, with his Marginal Revolution co-blogger

00:01:17.040 --> 00:01:21.360
[Amit Varma]: Alex Tabarrok, who has been a guest on the Scene and the Unseen a couple of times.

00:01:21.360 --> 00:01:27.340
[Amit Varma]: The subject I invited Tyler to chat about is his latest book, Stubborn Attachments.

00:01:27.340 --> 00:01:31.920
[Amit Varma]: This is not actually a book of economics, but of moral philosophy.

00:01:31.920 --> 00:01:35.800
[Amit Varma]: In a nutshell, Tyler makes a number of bold assertions in this book.

00:01:35.800 --> 00:01:40.800
[Amit Varma]: One, he argues that we need to regard future lives of people who haven't yet been born

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:44.680
[Amit Varma]: as morally equivalent to the lives of those alive today.

00:01:44.680 --> 00:01:46.640
[Amit Varma]: We should not discount those lives at all.

00:01:46.640 --> 00:01:52.320
[Amit Varma]: Two, he argues that for this reason, aiming for high economic growth is a moral imperative,

00:01:52.320 --> 00:01:57.800
[Amit Varma]: as that will lead to the best outcomes for future humans, and so we need to build institutions

00:01:57.800 --> 00:02:03.880
[Amit Varma]: and social norms that maximize the chances of achieving sustainable high economic growth.

00:02:03.880 --> 00:02:08.820
[Amit Varma]: Three, he says that we should do all of this within the constraints of human rights, which

00:02:08.820 --> 00:02:11.200
[Amit Varma]: he defines to be negative rights.

00:02:11.200 --> 00:02:16.280
