[Amit Varma]: Happy to be here.

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:33.880
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

00:03:33.880 --> 00:03:36.760
[Amit Varma]: Tyler, my friends and I have a theory that there isn't actually one Tyler Carvin, it's

00:03:36.760 --> 00:03:41.440
[Amit Varma]: a collective that calls itself Tyler Carvin because you actually get so much done that

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:45.640
[Amit Varma]: it seems impossible one person could manage it all, you write multiple posts a day on

00:03:45.640 --> 00:03:50.720
[Amit Varma]: Marginal Revolution, you've written 15-16 books, you obviously read so much, you immerse

00:03:50.720 --> 00:03:54.240
[Amit Varma]: yourself in other cultures, you travel, you've written a book about food, so you eat out

00:03:54.240 --> 00:03:56.360
[Amit Varma]: a lot, and you teach.

00:03:56.360 --> 00:03:58.920
[Amit Varma]: So I'm really curious, how do you structure your days?

00:03:58.920 --> 00:04:01.840
[Amit Varma]: Like, what's a typical day in the life of Tyler Carvin like?

00:04:01.840 --> 00:04:08.200
[Guest]: I try to wake up at exactly the same time, by 7am at the latest.

00:04:08.200 --> 00:04:13.280
[Guest]: And then I start working right away, and every morning I treat writing as the most important

00:04:13.280 --> 00:04:14.880
[Guest]: thing I do.

00:04:14.880 --> 00:04:17.640
[Guest]: And I get some writing done.

00:04:17.640 --> 00:04:22.360
[Guest]: And then the afternoon, all kinds of things can happen, but other things get done then

00:04:22.360 --> 00:04:23.360
[Guest]: too.

00:04:23.360 --> 00:04:28.960
[Guest]: And, you know, you stop maybe by 11pm and you go to bed.

00:04:28.960 --> 00:04:33.240
[Guest]: I exercise somewhere in between, obviously I eat.

00:04:33.240 --> 00:04:35.560
[Amit Varma]: That would be like a first cut at it.

00:04:35.560 --> 00:04:40.560
[Amit Varma]: Do you set out a specific time for reading, or do you just read as and when you can?

00:04:40.560 --> 00:04:43.720
[Guest]: When I can, but I really never read in the morning.

00:04:43.720 --> 00:04:44.720
[Guest]: Mornings are for writing.

00:04:44.720 --> 00:04:47.040
[Guest]: Now, when I travel, it's quite different.

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:52.200
[Guest]: I may just spend the whole day walking around, you know, looking, say, at Mumbai or wherever,

00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:56.660
[Guest]: taking in things in a more intensive way than I could when I'm reading.

00:04:56.660 --> 00:05:00.760
[Amit Varma]: And I read in an interview of yours that, you know, a lot of the books you read, you

00:05:00.760 --> 00:05:05.840
[Amit Varma]: sort of, you know, you don't necessarily read all of them, but there are a few books that

00:05:05.840 --> 00:05:09.640
[Amit Varma]: you really like that you go back to when you read them multiple times.

00:05:09.640 --> 00:05:13.680
[Amit Varma]: What are the sort of books that through your life have really, either A, books which have

00:05:13.680 --> 00:05:17.720
[Amit Varma]: influenced you and influenced your thinking, and B, books which you just like to read and

00:05:17.720 --> 00:05:18.920
[Guest]: reread again for pleasure?

00:05:18.920 --> 00:05:23.400
[Guest]: Well, I'm reading for maybe the fifth or sixth time Homer's Odyssey.

00:05:23.400 --> 00:05:28.040
[Guest]: There's a new translation by Emily Wilson, and I'm enjoying that a great deal.

00:05:28.040 --> 00:05:33.760
[Guest]: The books I like to reread typically are very famous classic books like Adam Smith or Plato,

00:05:33.760 --> 00:05:35.640
[Guest]: Gulliver's Travels by Jonathan Swift.

00:05:35.640 --> 00:05:38.000
[Guest]: They wouldn't be that hard to guess at.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:41.520
[Guest]: Most books that come out today, you know, maybe they should have been articles.

00:05:41.520 --> 00:05:45.720
[Guest]: They may have good parts or a chapter on a topic or country you're interested in, but

00:05:45.720 --> 00:05:47.840
[Amit Varma]: I don't see why you should read the whole thing.

00:05:47.840 --> 00:05:48.840
[Amit Varma]: That's true.

00:05:48.840 --> 00:05:52.040
[Amit Varma]: And is there any book or are there any books that sort of were like a eureka moment for

00:05:52.040 --> 00:05:54.080
[Guest]: you that changed the way you look at the world?

00:05:54.080 --> 00:05:59.240
[Guest]: Well, reading Plato's Dialogues when I was 13 and 14 years old, that had really a big

00:05:59.240 --> 00:06:00.720
[Guest]: impact on me.

00:06:00.720 --> 00:06:06.440
[Guest]: It got me thinking more philosophically, and it just introduced me to Western thought and

00:06:06.440 --> 00:06:08.580
[Guest]: the idea of dialogue.

00:06:08.580 --> 00:06:14.440
[Guest]: So that Adam Smith, reading Hayek when I was quite young, those would be some of like the

00:06:14.440 --> 00:06:16.400
[Amit Varma]: earthquake moments for me.

00:06:16.400 --> 00:06:21.160
[Amit Varma]: And also, I mean, you've written 15 or 16 books, and one often assumes that, you know,

00:06:21.160 --> 00:06:24.200
[Amit Varma]: when you write a book, you come up with the idea of a book, you spend a couple of years

00:06:24.200 --> 00:06:25.200
[Amit Varma]: and you write it.

00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:30.480
[Amit Varma]: But in the case of Stubborn Attachments, I read that you spent, you know, more than 20

00:06:30.480 --> 00:06:36.520
[Amit Varma]: years actually thinking about this book, writing drafts of it, and, you know, getting it together

00:06:36.520 --> 00:06:39.120
[Amit Varma]: in your head before you actually came out with the book.

00:06:39.120 --> 00:06:43.560
[Amit Varma]: Can you sort of take me on your intellectual journey through the questions of this book?

00:06:43.560 --> 00:06:47.560
[Amit Varma]: Like, what are the big questions in this book that you were trying to answer that concerned

00:06:47.560 --> 00:06:48.560
[Amit Varma]: you?

00:06:48.560 --> 00:06:51.800
[Amit Varma]: And did you come up with different answers to those questions at any point?

00:06:51.800 --> 00:06:56.640
[Guest]: When I was at Harvard in 1984, I was in Harvard bookstore.

00:06:56.640 --> 00:07:01.160
[Guest]: And just coincidentally, I picked up a copy of Derek Barfitt's Reasons and Persons, which

00:07:01.160 --> 00:07:03.700
[Guest]: is still one of my favorite books.

00:07:03.700 --> 00:07:07.860
[Guest]: And that book was another of these earthquake moments.

00:07:07.860 --> 00:07:12.360
[Guest]: And that was just his take, you know, on the self and how to think about value and how

00:07:12.360 --> 00:07:15.320
[Guest]: to aggregate or not aggregate.

00:07:15.320 --> 00:07:19.400
[Guest]: And I just thought, well, I need to spend a big chunk of my life in some way responding

00:07:19.400 --> 00:07:21.760
[Guest]: to this book or addressing it.

00:07:21.760 --> 00:07:27.480
[Guest]: So the issues I've been thinking about since 1984 and about 20 years ago, I think I've

00:07:27.480 --> 00:07:33.680
[Guest]: now lost track exactly how long, I started writing a manuscript on the value of civilization.

00:07:33.680 --> 00:07:37.000
[Guest]: That would be my account of what value is.

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:41.320
[Guest]: And I thought, well, you know, a book like this, I can't just finish it in two or three

00:07:41.320 --> 00:07:42.320
[Guest]: years.

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:46.140
[Guest]: I've got to work with, I'll need to think about for a long time, talk about with many

00:07:46.140 --> 00:07:51.440
[Guest]: other people, see, you know, much more what has been published on the topic.

00:07:51.440 --> 00:07:55.160
[Guest]: So just every year, I would spend about a month revising.

00:07:55.160 --> 00:07:56.960
[Guest]: And this book kept on changing.

00:07:56.960 --> 00:08:00.760
[Guest]: A lot of the time, the changes were just me cutting things.

00:08:00.760 --> 00:08:02.000
[Guest]: And finally, it's come out.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:03.920
[Guest]: So I'm very happy about that.

00:08:03.920 --> 00:08:06.920
[Guest]: But a lot of my books are these like longer term investments.

00:08:06.920 --> 00:08:09.960
[Guest]: You know, my book on food, I didn't spend that long writing it.

00:08:09.960 --> 00:08:15.320
[Guest]: But I spent many years eating, and it's really the distillation of what I learned, you know,

00:08:15.320 --> 00:08:16.680
[Guest]: traveling and eating.

00:08:16.680 --> 00:08:20.600
[Amit Varma]: So in that sense, that's another very long production period.

00:08:20.600 --> 00:08:22.200
[Amit Varma]: And that's actually a really lovely short book.

00:08:22.200 --> 00:08:26.360
[Amit Varma]: I quote from it often when I go out to eat, in fact, let's kind of talk about stubborn

00:08:26.360 --> 00:08:27.680
[Amit Varma]: attachments.

00:08:27.680 --> 00:08:31.480
[Amit Varma]: What's the central question that you're trying to answer through this book?

00:08:31.480 --> 00:08:34.940
[Guest]: What is the correct way to think about the best society?

00:08:34.940 --> 00:08:41.000
[Guest]: What standard could we plausibly use to judge one social outcome as better than another?

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:44.760
[Guest]: And finally, what kind of thinking should guide economic policy?

00:08:44.760 --> 00:08:49.800
[Guest]: And I decide that this notion of compound returns and economic growth is really central

00:08:49.800 --> 00:08:52.240
[Guest]: to solving all of those puzzles.

00:08:52.240 --> 00:08:55.120
[Guest]: So it's very much a pro-economic growth book.

00:08:55.120 --> 00:08:56.120
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:08:56.120 --> 00:09:00.880
[Amit Varma]: And you write about this concept called the crosonia plant in the book as a metaphor for

00:09:00.880 --> 00:09:01.880
[Guest]: economic growth.

00:09:01.880 --> 00:09:06.240
[Guest]: Yes, think of the crosonia plant as representing compound returns.

00:09:06.240 --> 00:09:10.520
[Guest]: So say you have an apple tree and the apple tree gives you apples and the apples in turn

00:09:10.520 --> 00:09:12.080
[Guest]: give you more apple trees.

00:09:12.080 --> 00:09:16.480
[Guest]: There's this notion of things which, of their own steam, keep on growing forever and give

00:09:16.480 --> 00:09:18.280
[Guest]: you more and more value.

00:09:18.280 --> 00:09:20.440
[Guest]: And a well-structured economy is one of those.

00:09:20.440 --> 00:09:26.960
[Guest]: And I argue we can think of those as the fundamental sources of value at the social level in human

00:09:26.960 --> 00:09:28.120
[Guest]: affairs.

00:09:28.120 --> 00:09:34.040
[Guest]: And the one definitive claim we can make is that an economy which is much wealthier is

00:09:34.040 --> 00:09:38.120
[Guest]: clearly better than an economy or society which is much poorer.

00:09:38.120 --> 00:09:42.760
[Amit Varma]: And this is a sort of a debate that keeps cropping up because despite the overwhelming

00:09:42.760 --> 00:09:48.240
[Amit Varma]: evidence that points out that wealth and social welfare are completely correlated and it's

00:09:48.240 --> 00:09:54.560
[Amit Varma]: very clear that economic growth causes people to live better lives, it's still something

00:09:54.560 --> 00:09:57.680
[Amit Varma]: that's oddly enough questioned in many circles.

00:09:57.680 --> 00:09:58.680
[Amit Varma]: Why do you think that is?

00:09:58.680 --> 00:10:01.520
[Amit Varma]: Why that skepticism when the data is so clear?

00:10:01.520 --> 00:10:09.240
[Guest]: I think there are a number of reasons why people are reluctant to accept a more optimistic

00:10:09.240 --> 00:10:15.080
[Guest]: outlook or the notion that a lot of other values can be subsumed by having some form

00:10:15.080 --> 00:10:16.920
[Guest]: of economic growth.

00:10:16.920 --> 00:10:22.640
[Guest]: I think a lot of people, they're programmed to want to complain and they end up with other

00:10:22.640 --> 00:10:23.640
[Guest]: views.

00:10:23.640 --> 00:10:25.680
[Guest]: But this is why I called the book Stubborn Attachments.

00:10:25.680 --> 00:10:31.240
[Guest]: I argue we should literally have a stubborn attachment to this idea of growth and also

00:10:31.240 --> 00:10:33.640
[Guest]: to an idea of human rights.

00:10:33.640 --> 00:10:35.640
[Amit Varma]: And you know, stick with them stubbornly.

00:10:35.640 --> 00:10:36.640
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:10:36.640 --> 00:10:43.880
[Amit Varma]: And you also sort of make the case that measuring economic growth of wealth through GDP itself

00:10:43.880 --> 00:10:45.560
[Amit Varma]: is insufficient.

00:10:45.560 --> 00:10:47.800
[Amit Varma]: And you talk about something which you call wealth plus.

00:10:47.800 --> 00:10:50.200
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about wealth plus.

00:10:50.200 --> 00:10:53.680
[Amit Varma]: What more does it have besides GDP and how do we measure it?

00:10:53.680 --> 00:10:59.080
[Guest]: Well, to give an example from India, some parts of India, such as Kerala, are in some

00:10:59.080 --> 00:11:03.540
[Guest]: ways better off than just numerical wealth might indicate.

00:11:03.540 --> 00:11:07.440
[Guest]: So they have stronger social indicators.

00:11:07.440 --> 00:11:12.160
[Guest]: Environmental factors may be something else that's not fully captured in GDP or leisure

00:11:12.160 --> 00:11:13.160
[Guest]: time.

00:11:13.160 --> 00:11:16.040
[Guest]: So I think GDP is actually a fine number for many purposes.

00:11:16.040 --> 00:11:18.400
[Guest]: It often comes close enough.

00:11:18.400 --> 00:11:25.080
[Guest]: But for some final decisions, we need to also incorporate social indicators, the value of

00:11:25.080 --> 00:11:27.720
[Guest]: the environment, and also leisure time.

00:11:27.720 --> 00:11:29.960
[Amit Varma]: So that's how I would modify GDP.

00:11:29.960 --> 00:11:31.080
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:11:31.080 --> 00:11:36.120
[Amit Varma]: And you sort of write in your book that because, you know, compound interest is something that

00:11:36.120 --> 00:11:42.360
[Amit Varma]: is so underestimated and, you know, you point out about how if you ask someone by how much

00:11:42.360 --> 00:11:46.360
[Amit Varma]: has the standard of living in America gone up in the last hundred years that your typical

00:11:46.360 --> 00:11:51.200
[Amit Varma]: guesstimate of someone you ask could be, what, 50% a couple of times, but it's actually seven

00:11:51.200 --> 00:11:56.560
[Amit Varma]: eight times because people underestimate the value of compound interest and also a lot

00:11:56.560 --> 00:12:01.120
[Amit Varma]: of the growth, I guess, can't be quantified because the remarkable amount of information

00:12:01.120 --> 00:12:05.800
[Amit Varma]: that you can access on your smartphone, for example, or the fact that no human being will

00:12:05.800 --> 00:12:08.680
[Amit Varma]: ever get lost again because of technology.

00:12:08.680 --> 00:12:10.200
[Amit Varma]: You know, how do you quantify that stuff?

00:12:10.200 --> 00:12:12.840
[Amit Varma]: There's no economic figure that can capture that.

00:12:12.840 --> 00:12:18.200
[Guest]: I agree with that, but I think for actual comparisons, if you simply look at GDP growth

00:12:18.200 --> 00:12:24.160
[Guest]: rates over time and again, adjust them a small amount, they come close enough.

00:12:24.160 --> 00:12:29.760
[Guest]: So the countries that measure as having the highest GDP really are the countries with

00:12:29.760 --> 00:12:31.760
[Guest]: the highest living standards.

00:12:31.760 --> 00:12:35.480
[Guest]: Maybe the oil monarchies would be somewhat of an exception to that.

00:12:35.480 --> 00:12:40.480
[Guest]: But if you look at the United States, Canada, Australia, Norway, those are the places where

00:12:40.480 --> 00:12:45.120
[Guest]: people want to migrate to if they can, and they're the places with high GDP.

00:12:45.120 --> 00:12:47.880
[Guest]: So I think the measure works surprisingly well.

00:12:47.880 --> 00:12:51.520
[Guest]: It doesn't mean that money is all that matters or even the main thing.

00:12:51.520 --> 00:12:56.600
[Guest]: But as you mentioned, GDP correlates with having a more secure life, lower levels of

00:12:56.600 --> 00:13:03.200
[Guest]: stress, a more rewarding or safer, more creative job, many, many other non-monetary goods.

00:13:03.200 --> 00:13:08.480
[Amit Varma]: And there'll be naysayers on the left who will sort of say that, hey, economic growth

00:13:08.480 --> 00:13:12.440
[Amit Varma]: is all well and fine, but it's not across the board, there's inequality.

00:13:12.440 --> 00:13:16.000
[Amit Varma]: What about those who are left behind and so on and so forth?

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:19.920
[Guest]: The best remedy for those who are left behind is economic growth.

00:13:19.920 --> 00:13:21.640
[Guest]: You see this in the history of China.

00:13:21.640 --> 00:13:29.720
[Guest]: The Chinese economy is about 40 times larger than it was, you know, about 50 years ago.

00:13:29.720 --> 00:13:31.640
[Guest]: That's just astonishing.

00:13:31.640 --> 00:13:35.640
[Guest]: China not only has more billionaires than the United States, but it has a healthy and

00:13:35.640 --> 00:13:37.480
[Guest]: growing middle class.

00:13:37.480 --> 00:13:41.880
[Guest]: And Chinese rural areas are also much, much better off than they had been where there

00:13:41.880 --> 00:13:43.900
[Guest]: used to be starvation.

00:13:43.900 --> 00:13:46.280
[Guest]: People now eat really very well.

00:13:46.280 --> 00:13:50.560
[Guest]: So again, if you're asking what's the one thing we can do that's better for virtually

00:13:50.560 --> 00:13:55.600
[Guest]: everyone, I think the unique answer which stands out is economic growth.

00:13:55.600 --> 00:13:56.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:13:56.600 --> 00:14:01.880
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I, you know, when talking about inequality, I tend to say that it's a luxury of rich countries

00:14:01.880 --> 00:14:06.160
[Amit Varma]: to think about it, that people in India should just focus on poverty, which is a very different

00:14:06.160 --> 00:14:10.720
[Amit Varma]: problem and inequality and poverty are very different, they require different solutions.

00:14:10.720 --> 00:14:16.080
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, I often I mean, one clear indicator of this is that, you know, you don't see any

00:14:16.080 --> 00:14:20.400
[Amit Varma]: poor people trying to migrate to Bangladesh, they're trying to migrate to the US.

00:14:20.400 --> 00:14:24.380
[Amit Varma]: And similarly, you don't see any migration away from cities, you see them migrating to

00:14:24.380 --> 00:14:29.480
[Amit Varma]: cities and if inequality was a big problem, that should have been the other way around.

00:14:29.480 --> 00:14:30.480
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:14:30.480 --> 00:14:35.680
[Guest]: And even in the US, I mean, most ordinary Americans don't care about inequality.

00:14:35.680 --> 00:14:40.200
[Guest]: They care about whether or not they have a good job or growing wages.

00:14:40.200 --> 00:14:44.720
[Guest]: If they care about inequality, they compare themselves to their high school classmates,

00:14:44.720 --> 00:14:46.960
[Guest]: you know, not to billionaires or Bill Gates.

00:14:46.960 --> 00:14:51.320
[Guest]: So the inequalities that people actually get bothered by are quite local.

00:14:51.320 --> 00:14:54.880
[Amit Varma]: They're within families or all groups of friends or peers.

00:14:54.880 --> 00:14:59.440
[Amit Varma]: And you know, often people also say that, look, you know, economic growth is all well

00:14:59.440 --> 00:15:01.920
[Amit Varma]: and fine, but money can't buy happiness.

00:15:01.920 --> 00:15:05.840
[Amit Varma]: Can happiness be measured and is that something that you'd agree with?

00:15:05.840 --> 00:15:11.460
[Guest]: I wouldn't say money can buy happiness, but having a wealthier society is the best thing

00:15:11.460 --> 00:15:14.240
[Guest]: you can do to get higher levels of happiness.

00:15:14.240 --> 00:15:19.280
[Guest]: So it just gives people a more secure foundation for other things they wish to do to seek their

00:15:19.280 --> 00:15:20.400
[Guest]: happiness.

00:15:20.400 --> 00:15:24.840
[Guest]: So I would say, you know, it's steps A, B and C, if your goal is to just make people

00:15:24.840 --> 00:15:25.840
[Guest]: happy.

00:15:25.840 --> 00:15:26.840
[Guest]: Now, I'm an ethical pluralist.

00:15:26.840 --> 00:15:29.160
[Guest]: I don't think happiness is the only value.

00:15:29.160 --> 00:15:33.160
[Guest]: I think aesthetics, creativity, justice, all these things matter.

00:15:33.160 --> 00:15:37.560
[Guest]: But for the most part, they also do better in these wealthier societies.

00:15:37.560 --> 00:15:43.120
[Amit Varma]: And you also pointed out that, you know, people often measure happiness through surveys by

00:15:43.120 --> 00:15:45.320
[Amit Varma]: asking people if they are happy.

00:15:45.320 --> 00:15:48.680
[Amit Varma]: And you know, that measurement leads to a sort of a language problem.

00:15:48.680 --> 00:15:52.240
[Amit Varma]: Like you correctly said, you know, a poor person in Kenya who's relatively better off

00:15:52.240 --> 00:15:56.520
[Amit Varma]: than his neighbors might actually rate higher on the happiness scale, according to how he

00:15:56.520 --> 00:16:02.480
[Amit Varma]: sees himself, than an American who in reality is actually far better off and even happier,

00:16:02.480 --> 00:16:04.480
[Guest]: though he doesn't express it that way.

00:16:04.480 --> 00:16:05.480
[Guest]: That's right.

00:16:05.480 --> 00:16:10.840
[Guest]: I think when you look at numerous other indicators, such as what people actually choose, the case

00:16:10.840 --> 00:16:15.080
[Guest]: that wealth is correlated with happiness is really pretty strong.

00:16:15.080 --> 00:16:18.960
[Guest]: Wealthier societies, there's also greater life expectancy.

00:16:18.960 --> 00:16:22.720
[Guest]: So you just live longer, you have more years of whatever level of happiness you're going

00:16:22.720 --> 00:16:23.720
[Guest]: to have.

00:16:23.720 --> 00:16:27.240
[Guest]: And these measures don't pick that up, because the questionnaires, you're only asking people

00:16:27.240 --> 00:16:29.360
[Amit Varma]: who are alive, right?

00:16:29.360 --> 00:16:34.480
[Amit Varma]: And you know, another thing that you've kind of pointed out is that, you know, this is

00:16:34.480 --> 00:16:38.680
[Amit Varma]: like you say that there are three questions that we should ask ourselves when deciding

00:16:38.680 --> 00:16:39.680
[Amit Varma]: on what we should do.

00:16:39.680 --> 00:16:44.400
[Amit Varma]: And those three questions are, A, what can we do to boost the rate of economic growth?

00:16:44.400 --> 00:16:47.680
[Amit Varma]: B, what can we do to make our civilization more stable?

00:16:47.680 --> 00:16:51.280
[Amit Varma]: C, how should we deal with our environmental problems?

00:16:51.280 --> 00:16:54.280
[Amit Varma]: Because this obviously has an effect on future generations.

00:16:54.280 --> 00:16:57.520
[Amit Varma]: And as you pointed out, you know, the first of those questions about economic growth is

00:16:57.520 --> 00:17:00.480
[Amit Varma]: something that libertarians would be attracted to.

00:17:00.480 --> 00:17:04.920
[Amit Varma]: The second of those about civilizations being more stable is more something that would appeal

00:17:04.920 --> 00:17:09.960
[Amit Varma]: more to conservatives and environmental problems more to left wingers.

00:17:09.960 --> 00:17:15.880
[Amit Varma]: And the fact that you sort of require a consensus on all of these, if this vision is to be sort

00:17:15.880 --> 00:17:20.380
[Amit Varma]: of accepted as a moral vision, isn't that more of a bug than a feature?

00:17:20.380 --> 00:17:25.320
[Amit Varma]: Because now we are divided into political tribes, and you're never actually going to

00:17:25.320 --> 00:17:30.760
[Amit Varma]: get anyone to agree with something that's a concern of the opposing political tribe

00:17:30.760 --> 00:17:31.760
[Amit Varma]: reflexively.

00:17:31.760 --> 00:17:36.200
[Guest]: Well, I'm not sure how many people will agree with me, but I think the important thing is

00:17:36.200 --> 00:17:38.880
[Guest]: to put out what you think is right.

00:17:38.880 --> 00:17:43.120
[Guest]: And the world political opinion isn't a bad way in today's world.

00:17:43.120 --> 00:17:48.080
[Guest]: In most countries, I guess I have the intuitive view that if what you're saying irritates

00:17:48.080 --> 00:17:52.020
[Guest]: everyone just a bit, maybe you're on the right track.

00:17:52.020 --> 00:17:55.320
[Guest]: And if you're just, you know, picking one of the sides and saying, rah, rah, this is

00:17:55.320 --> 00:17:57.480
[Guest]: my team, probably you're on the wrong track.

00:17:57.480 --> 00:18:01.600
[Guest]: Now, that doesn't mean my view is right.

00:18:01.600 --> 00:18:05.800
[Guest]: But again, the goal is not to persuade people in the short term, that may be hopeless.

00:18:05.800 --> 00:18:10.080
[Guest]: But sort of the long term, how people think about the world a generation from now, I hope

00:18:10.080 --> 00:18:13.600
[Amit Varma]: is along the lines I'm suggesting ideas do change.

00:18:13.600 --> 00:18:17.440
[Amit Varma]: And you sort of told me that, you know, one of the earthquake books for you, so to say,

00:18:17.440 --> 00:18:18.680
[Amit Varma]: was Plato's dialogues.

00:18:18.680 --> 00:18:23.480
[Amit Varma]: But in today's times, given what discourse has become, is Socratic dialogue even possible?

00:18:23.480 --> 00:18:28.640
[Amit Varma]: I mean, what social media has done is it's enabled all of us to find these echo chambers.

00:18:28.640 --> 00:18:34.240
[Amit Varma]: And you often find that, you know, social media, especially, and all of political discourse

00:18:34.240 --> 00:18:38.240
[Amit Varma]: really is incredibly polarized, where people aren't talking to each other anymore.

00:18:38.240 --> 00:18:40.040
[Amit Varma]: They're talking past each other.

00:18:40.040 --> 00:18:44.040
[Amit Varma]: They're posturing to raise their stature in their in group, are the days of Socratic dialogue

00:18:44.040 --> 00:18:45.040
[Amit Varma]: behind us?

00:18:45.040 --> 00:18:48.920
[Guest]: Well, people sometimes say that, but I'm not convinced it's gotten any worse.

00:18:48.920 --> 00:18:51.000
[Guest]: And in a lot of ways, it's better.

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:53.760
[Guest]: So you can use the internet to reach out to anyone.

00:18:53.760 --> 00:18:59.600
[Guest]: I mean, you emailed me to set up this Skype call and podcast, probably, we don't agree

00:18:59.600 --> 00:19:00.760
[Guest]: on a bunch of things.

00:19:00.760 --> 00:19:02.520
[Guest]: But here we are talking.

00:19:02.520 --> 00:19:07.200
[Guest]: And go back to the 1970s, where there's, you know, no internet, there's television, which

00:19:07.200 --> 00:19:12.440
[Guest]: is awful in the US, just three major networks, it's all boring and stupid and mainstream.

00:19:12.440 --> 00:19:17.120
[Guest]: It was very hard to like break into, you know, writing for newspapers, I think it's much

00:19:17.120 --> 00:19:18.620
[Guest]: better now.

00:19:18.620 --> 00:19:23.720
[Guest]: So partly because like the pond is so much bigger, you have more ideologues and more

00:19:23.720 --> 00:19:27.560
[Amit Varma]: intolerance, but you also have much, much more real dialogue.

00:19:27.560 --> 00:19:31.760
[Amit Varma]: Moving on back to your book now, you know, one of the controversial points you made was

00:19:31.760 --> 00:19:37.040
[Amit Varma]: about time preferences about how, you know, we all tend naturally to discount the long

00:19:37.040 --> 00:19:41.840
[Amit Varma]: term, and think of the short term, and this is especially true when it comes to all the

00:19:41.840 --> 00:19:45.960
[Amit Varma]: people who are alive today versus all the people who might live 200, 300, 400 years

00:19:45.960 --> 00:19:47.240
[Amit Varma]: from now.

00:19:47.240 --> 00:19:48.800
[Amit Varma]: And we discount the value to them.

00:19:48.800 --> 00:19:54.160
[Amit Varma]: And what we do is not with reference to the kind of lives that they will have.

00:19:54.160 --> 00:19:59.520
[Amit Varma]: And your dual argument is that number one, we should treat those lives as equivalent

00:19:59.520 --> 00:20:01.760
[Amit Varma]: or almost equivalent.

00:20:01.760 --> 00:20:07.200
[Amit Varma]: And we should design our policies and our actions accordingly.

00:20:07.200 --> 00:20:08.200
[Guest]: That's right.

00:20:08.200 --> 00:20:12.640
[Guest]: And I think what that means in practical terms, is the best thing we can do for the future

00:20:12.640 --> 00:20:17.720
[Guest]: is to invest in better institutions and better rules and norms today.

00:20:17.720 --> 00:20:22.360
[Guest]: It's not that we can control future events 30, 40 years out in any kind of fine detailed

00:20:22.360 --> 00:20:24.220
[Guest]: predictable way.

00:20:24.220 --> 00:20:29.440
[Guest]: But we should have this obsession on making our procedures and processes as good as possible.

00:20:29.440 --> 00:20:32.840
[Amit Varma]: And I think that is exactly the right advice.

00:20:32.840 --> 00:20:38.200
[Amit Varma]: And that actually goes against both, I mean, as you correctly pointed out, people are wired

00:20:38.200 --> 00:20:42.280
[Amit Varma]: to think of the short term, possibly because we evolved in prehistoric times.

00:20:42.280 --> 00:20:45.880
[Amit Varma]: And in the hunter gatherer rage, it's you know, you're going to survive longer if you

00:20:45.880 --> 00:20:51.720
[Amit Varma]: think of the short term imperative of surviving rather than think 10-20 years into the future.

00:20:51.720 --> 00:20:54.720
[Amit Varma]: So one, people think automatically in the short term.

00:20:54.720 --> 00:20:59.120
[Amit Varma]: And two, when you think of the political economy, if you just look at what the incentives for

00:20:59.120 --> 00:21:03.520
[Amit Varma]: political parties are like, every party just gives a damn about one thing.

00:21:03.520 --> 00:21:06.640
[Amit Varma]: They want to win the next election, they don't really care.

00:21:06.640 --> 00:21:11.880
[Amit Varma]: I mean, just to take an example from India, which is going on these days, is that it has

00:21:11.880 --> 00:21:17.360
[Amit Varma]: now become the rigor for any party which wants to win elections, to offer farm loan waivers

00:21:17.360 --> 00:21:18.760
[Amit Varma]: to farmers.

00:21:18.760 --> 00:21:22.680
[Amit Varma]: And farmers, of course, are I mean, we are in the middle of an agricultural crisis, farmers

00:21:22.680 --> 00:21:27.280
[Amit Varma]: are in great distress, it's completely natural for them to ask for farm loan waivers.

00:21:27.280 --> 00:21:31.280
[Amit Varma]: And it's completely natural, therefore, for the supply side of the political marketplace

00:21:31.280 --> 00:21:33.600
[Amit Varma]: to promise them those farm loan waivers.

00:21:33.600 --> 00:21:37.760
[Amit Varma]: And rationally, everybody can sort of say that, look, this is not really good for the

00:21:37.760 --> 00:21:41.440
[Amit Varma]: long term, what we need to do for the long term is we need to do structural reforms and

00:21:41.440 --> 00:21:42.760
[Amit Varma]: blah, blah, blah.

00:21:42.760 --> 00:21:45.760
[Amit Varma]: But there's no demand for that in electoral politics.

00:21:45.760 --> 00:21:50.960
[Amit Varma]: Thinking of the long term just doesn't come naturally either to individuals, and it doesn't

00:21:50.960 --> 00:21:54.040
[Amit Varma]: make sense to politicians to cater for it.

00:21:54.040 --> 00:21:58.160
[Amit Varma]: So even if people agree with you at a rational level, that yes, this is how we should think

00:21:58.160 --> 00:22:03.760
[Amit Varma]: to be moral beings, how does that find expression in actual action?

00:22:03.760 --> 00:22:08.760
[Guest]: This same kind of problem is becoming worse in my country as well in my politics.

00:22:08.760 --> 00:22:13.120
[Guest]: But what I find striking is you have many countries, often democracies, where it's not

00:22:13.120 --> 00:22:14.520
[Guest]: nearly as bad.

00:22:14.520 --> 00:22:21.680
[Guest]: If you look at Norway or Switzerland, or New Zealand, Singapore is not not quite a full

00:22:21.680 --> 00:22:26.040
[Guest]: normal democracy, but nonetheless, they have good governance.

00:22:26.040 --> 00:22:28.760
[Guest]: They do have much longer time perspectives.

00:22:28.760 --> 00:22:33.040
[Guest]: And I don't, in every case, know what the secret is for that difference in perspective,

00:22:33.040 --> 00:22:35.280
[Guest]: but I think it shows it's possible.

00:22:35.280 --> 00:22:40.320
[Guest]: So I would just like to see American political debate reoriented much more along this idea

00:22:40.320 --> 00:22:42.160
[Amit Varma]: of economic growth.

00:22:42.160 --> 00:22:43.400
[Amit Varma]: And do you see that happening?

00:22:43.400 --> 00:22:44.800
[Amit Varma]: Or is it going in the wrong direction?

00:22:44.800 --> 00:22:49.560
[Amit Varma]: Or do you at some level believe that the arc of history, despite these little, you know,

00:22:49.560 --> 00:22:52.600
[Amit Varma]: ups and downs eventually moves towards freedom?

00:22:52.600 --> 00:22:56.920
[Guest]: I think in my country, it's going in the wrong direction, the world as a whole, it's probably

00:22:56.920 --> 00:23:00.040
[Guest]: still moving in a more positive direction.

00:23:00.040 --> 00:23:04.640
[Guest]: You have so many countries now trying to achieve economic growth, even if they're failing.

00:23:04.640 --> 00:23:09.760
[Guest]: And you look at a place like Ethiopia, they've now had 10 years in a row of averaging about

00:23:09.760 --> 00:23:11.880
[Guest]: 10% growth a year.

00:23:11.880 --> 00:23:13.040
[Guest]: And that's fantastic.

00:23:13.040 --> 00:23:19.000
[Guest]: Something like that never would have or could have happened in the 70s, 80s, or even 1990s.

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:20.000
[Guest]: So I think I'm optimistic.

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:22.040
[Guest]: But you know, there's not a set answer.

00:23:22.040 --> 00:23:23.040
[Guest]: It is up to us.

00:23:23.040 --> 00:23:27.360
[Guest]: And a lot of countries, they get wealthy, and they grow sloppy in their thinking.

00:23:27.360 --> 00:23:29.320
[Guest]: And that's what's happened in America.

00:23:29.320 --> 00:23:30.320
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:23:30.320 --> 00:23:35.600
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, in your book, when you make the case for valuing future lives, as importantly

00:23:35.600 --> 00:23:39.960
[Amit Varma]: as current lives, there's a really nice quote by you, a start quote, imagine finding out

00:23:39.960 --> 00:23:45.440
[Amit Varma]: that you having just reached your 21st birthday, must soon die of cancer, because Cleopatra

00:23:45.440 --> 00:23:48.120
[Amit Varma]: wanted an extra helping of desert.

00:23:48.120 --> 00:23:49.120
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:23:49.120 --> 00:23:52.080
[Amit Varma]: And here, of course, you're sort of putting the reader in the place of a person in the

00:23:52.080 --> 00:23:56.720
[Amit Varma]: future and saying that, look, that person matters also, and therefore your actions matter.

00:23:56.720 --> 00:24:02.960
[Amit Varma]: But if we go back into the past, you've made a case for, you know, that do past actions

00:24:02.960 --> 00:24:05.880
[Amit Varma]: and lives matter as much as present lives?

00:24:05.880 --> 00:24:09.920
[Guest]: I think it's striking how much persistence there is in cultures.

00:24:09.920 --> 00:24:16.360
[Guest]: So there's a paper by Bill Easterly showing that per capita income in the year 500 AD

00:24:16.360 --> 00:24:20.480
[Guest]: actually has a fair amount of predictive power for per capita income today.

00:24:20.480 --> 00:24:24.920
[Guest]: So if you look at, say, the countries that were part of the Roman Empire way back when,

00:24:24.920 --> 00:24:28.720
[Guest]: compared to the rest of the world, they're still doing relatively well.

00:24:28.720 --> 00:24:30.040
[Guest]: China is rising again.

00:24:30.040 --> 00:24:32.800
[Guest]: It has earlier traditions that can draw upon.

00:24:32.800 --> 00:24:37.560
[Guest]: So just the persistence of the quality of the decisions we make today, I think, is often

00:24:37.560 --> 00:24:38.560
[Amit Varma]: underrated.

00:24:38.560 --> 00:24:42.880
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, and a sort of unrelated question, not something that has to do with the argument

00:24:42.880 --> 00:24:46.680
[Amit Varma]: we're making, but it just struck me when I was reading these bits, is that do you think

00:24:46.680 --> 00:24:52.960
[Amit Varma]: at some level, we should also discount past lives completely in the sense, let's say that

00:24:52.960 --> 00:24:55.000
[Amit Varma]: past lives and actions don't matter?

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:58.760
[Amit Varma]: Because what we sort of see in India, and no doubt across the world, but, you know,

00:24:58.760 --> 00:25:04.780
[Amit Varma]: with reference to India, is that there is this constant vicious cycle of the past being

00:25:04.780 --> 00:25:05.780
[Amit Varma]: invoked.

00:25:05.780 --> 00:25:10.400
[Amit Varma]: For example, a few hundred years ago, a Mughal emperor, you know, broke a temple here allegedly

00:25:10.400 --> 00:25:11.400
[Amit Varma]: and built a mosque.

00:25:11.400 --> 00:25:15.760
[Amit Varma]: We must now break the mosque and build a temple, which is something that the right will say,

00:25:15.760 --> 00:25:20.400
[Amit Varma]: or the left might say that, you know, Group A was oppressed by Group B. And therefore,

00:25:20.400 --> 00:25:26.040
[Amit Varma]: we now have to switch the oppression and recompense from it, which is a thinking in a very zero

00:25:26.040 --> 00:25:27.480
[Amit Varma]: some kind of way.

00:25:27.480 --> 00:25:32.360
[Amit Varma]: And B, it opens the gate for identity politics, which just vitiates the hatred between people

00:25:32.360 --> 00:25:35.640
[Amit Varma]: and doesn't help us move past that.

00:25:35.640 --> 00:25:36.640
[Guest]: Is that an issue?

00:25:36.640 --> 00:25:37.920
[Guest]: It's a huge issue.

00:25:37.920 --> 00:25:41.760
[Guest]: I don't think we'll ever succeed in really ignoring the past.

00:25:41.760 --> 00:25:46.320
[Guest]: Maybe a big part of me would like to, but I would say, let's pull the stories from the

00:25:46.320 --> 00:25:52.080
[Guest]: past and reinterpret those stories in a way that will do the most for us in the future.

00:25:52.080 --> 00:25:56.320
[Guest]: So a very, you know, positive vision of what we can become and how we can work together

00:25:56.320 --> 00:26:01.760
[Guest]: and how we can cooperate rather than these identity politics versions of the past.

00:26:01.760 --> 00:26:05.560
[Guest]: So I would rather have the past working for me, given that I cannot abolish it.

