00:27:43.040 --> 00:27:44.080
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen.

00:27:44.080 --> 00:27:45.880
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Tyler Cowen.

00:27:45.880 --> 00:27:51.800
[Amit Varma]: Tyler, the second big ingredient of your sort of the moral vision that you lay out.

00:27:51.800 --> 00:27:56.680
[Amit Varma]: The first ingredient, of course, is we must aim for economic growth because it compounds

00:27:56.680 --> 00:27:57.960
[Amit Varma]: over time.

00:27:57.960 --> 00:28:04.400
[Amit Varma]: And the second ingredient is we must, however, do this with the strong constraint of rights.

00:28:04.400 --> 00:28:06.680
[Amit Varma]: Can you explain that to me a little bit?

00:28:06.680 --> 00:28:08.160
[Amit Varma]: And also, what do you mean by rights?

00:28:08.160 --> 00:28:13.640
[Amit Varma]: Because people everywhere kind of get confused between positive and negative rights, and

00:28:13.640 --> 00:28:14.640
[Amit Varma]: it gets very muddy.

00:28:14.640 --> 00:28:19.680
[Guest]: I mean, negative rights, freedom from coercion and arbitrary murder.

00:28:19.680 --> 00:28:24.000
[Guest]: So just to be clear, most of the book is about economic growth, as I think our conversation

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:25.000
[Guest]: has indicated.

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:30.000
[Guest]: But there's a kind of rejoinder I was worried about, someone who might say, well, you know,

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:32.160
[Guest]: what about Joseph Stalin?

00:28:32.160 --> 00:28:36.320
[Guest]: He killed all these people, but it helped the Soviet Union grow at a rapid clip.

00:28:36.320 --> 00:28:40.960
[Guest]: Well, you know, I don't think it's true that Stalin killing people boosted Soviet economic

00:28:40.960 --> 00:28:41.960
[Guest]: growth.

00:28:41.960 --> 00:28:46.280
[Guest]: But the point I want to make in the book is not to argue that fact with people, but just

00:28:46.280 --> 00:28:48.880
[Guest]: to show that killing innocent people is wrong.

00:28:48.880 --> 00:28:52.000
[Guest]: You can have an absolute prohibition against it.

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:56.040
[Guest]: You don't have to think we should do that to get economic growth, that you have morals

00:28:56.040 --> 00:28:58.680
[Guest]: and you have the practical benefits of growth.

00:28:58.680 --> 00:29:02.360
[Guest]: And the right way to think about the world is to combine those two things and think of

00:29:02.360 --> 00:29:05.840
[Guest]: human rights as a constraint that you should operate within.

00:29:05.840 --> 00:29:06.840
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:29:06.840 --> 00:29:09.960
[Amit Varma]: And you talk about that constraint being nearly absolute.

00:29:09.960 --> 00:29:11.200
[Amit Varma]: What does it nearly indicate?

00:29:11.200 --> 00:29:15.560
[Guest]: Well, I think if there were some kind of strange case where to save the whole future history

00:29:15.560 --> 00:29:19.920
[Guest]: of the world, you had to kill some number of people, you know, maybe to fight World

00:29:19.920 --> 00:29:22.720
[Guest]: War Two, to stop Hitler from taking over the world.

00:29:22.720 --> 00:29:26.720
[Guest]: I think rights are embedded within the context of a world.

00:29:26.720 --> 00:29:31.120
[Guest]: And if you need to fight to save the world, you are then in some cases justified in infringing

00:29:31.120 --> 00:29:32.720
[Guest]: on people's rights.

00:29:32.720 --> 00:29:37.040
[Guest]: So if we had to have, say, a draft to fight World War Two, I mean, that did kill some

00:29:37.040 --> 00:29:38.240
[Guest]: innocent people.

00:29:38.240 --> 00:29:39.560
[Guest]: But I don't think that's wrong.

00:29:39.560 --> 00:29:40.560
[Guest]: Right.

00:29:40.560 --> 00:29:41.560
[Amit Varma]: But really, you need extreme cases.

00:29:41.560 --> 00:29:42.560
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:29:42.560 --> 00:29:46.080
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you mentioned that in your real world experience, you couldn't actually think of

00:29:46.080 --> 00:29:50.760
[Amit Varma]: extreme cases where, you know, infringing rights would be justified.

00:29:50.760 --> 00:29:52.240
[Amit Varma]: Not anything lately now.

00:29:52.240 --> 00:29:53.240
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:29:53.240 --> 00:29:59.440
[Amit Varma]: You then also have a chapter on a rather controversial subject of redistribution, where you talk

00:29:59.440 --> 00:30:05.920
[Amit Varma]: about our responsibility to the poor, and you talk about how some amount of redistribution

00:30:05.920 --> 00:30:09.160
[Amit Varma]: might be necessary, but not too much.

00:30:09.160 --> 00:30:10.160
[Amit Varma]: How does that work?

00:30:10.160 --> 00:30:12.240
[Amit Varma]: Like what amount is necessary?

00:30:12.240 --> 00:30:13.240
[Amit Varma]: And where do you draw the line?

00:30:13.240 --> 00:30:17.360
[Guest]: Well, a lot of redistribution actually boosts economic growth.

00:30:17.360 --> 00:30:23.120
[Guest]: So if you remove the risk of malnutrition from children, or give them better education,

00:30:23.120 --> 00:30:27.600
[Guest]: or maybe clean up a water system, those all have great potential to boost growth.

00:30:27.600 --> 00:30:30.480
[Guest]: And I'm all for that kind of activity.

00:30:30.480 --> 00:30:34.760
[Guest]: But that said, a lot of redistribution is just for redistribution's sake.

00:30:34.760 --> 00:30:36.360
[Guest]: It may make incentives worse.

00:30:36.360 --> 00:30:40.640
[Guest]: Poor people have less of an incentive to earn more income, wealthier people are taxed at

00:30:40.640 --> 00:30:43.480
[Guest]: higher rates, then I'm much more sceptical.

00:30:43.480 --> 00:30:47.640
[Guest]: So I would say let's do all the growth enhancing redistribution we can.

00:30:47.640 --> 00:30:51.960
[Amit Varma]: And you know, the question that then comes up there is that if we are balancing, say

00:30:51.960 --> 00:30:57.840
[Amit Varma]: the consequentialism of your essential vision against the rights that we say are a constraint

00:30:57.840 --> 00:31:03.800
[Amit Varma]: against that, any kind of redistribution does infringe negative rights in some way, because

00:31:03.800 --> 00:31:06.360
[Amit Varma]: obviously it's money coerced from people.

00:31:06.360 --> 00:31:08.120
[Guest]: How do you reconcile that?

00:31:08.120 --> 00:31:13.520
[Guest]: In my view, democratically voted taxation is not an infringement on rights per se.

00:31:13.520 --> 00:31:18.280
[Guest]: I mean, maybe it would be if it reached some level that were like extortion.

00:31:18.280 --> 00:31:23.400
[Guest]: But if people vote to tax themselves and provide some public goods, including redistribution,

00:31:23.400 --> 00:31:26.840
[Guest]: I don't per se consider that a violation of human rights.

00:31:26.840 --> 00:31:29.560
[Guest]: They may mess up, you know, whether it's done well or not.

00:31:29.560 --> 00:31:33.160
[Guest]: But in principle, it has the potential of making virtually all of us better off.

00:31:33.160 --> 00:31:38.240
[Amit Varma]: Right, but that's kind of, you know, if two wolves and goat have dinner together and the

00:31:38.240 --> 00:31:41.440
[Amit Varma]: wolves want to eat the goat and they take a vote on it, then you know, the majority

00:31:41.440 --> 00:31:46.640
[Amit Varma]: would want to eat the goat, but the goats rights would, you know, be infringed in that

00:31:46.640 --> 00:31:47.640
[Amit Varma]: sense.

00:31:47.640 --> 00:31:50.840
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the whole idea of negative rights is that you don't go by what the majority

00:31:50.840 --> 00:31:54.280
[Amit Varma]: wants, but you protect the rights of every individual.

00:31:54.280 --> 00:31:58.400
[Amit Varma]: And the whole, the sort of classical liberal vision of the state, I would imagine comes

00:31:58.400 --> 00:32:03.360
[Amit Varma]: from accepting that you do need a state to protect rights, and therefore that calls for

00:32:03.360 --> 00:32:05.840
[Amit Varma]: a necessary infringement of rights.

00:32:05.840 --> 00:32:09.120
[Amit Varma]: But anything beyond that becomes problematic.

00:32:09.120 --> 00:32:10.720
[Guest]: I would agree with most of that.

00:32:10.720 --> 00:32:13.520
[Guest]: I don't think there's an absolute right to all of your income.

00:32:13.520 --> 00:32:16.280
[Guest]: I do think there's a right to your life.

00:32:16.280 --> 00:32:21.400
[Guest]: But if you have, say, a government, which is reasonably accountable and based on democratic

00:32:21.400 --> 00:32:28.080
[Guest]: principles and it taxes from people say 30% of their income, I don't think that's an unjustifiable

00:32:28.080 --> 00:32:30.240
[Guest]: violation of rights.

00:32:30.240 --> 00:32:34.160
[Guest]: It's very different from say, rounding people up and putting them in camps and killing them.

00:32:34.160 --> 00:32:36.720
[Guest]: It's something you would like to minimize that taxation.

00:32:36.720 --> 00:32:41.320
[Guest]: But again, there's not actually an alternative that will give people more liberty.

00:32:41.320 --> 00:32:42.320
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:32:42.320 --> 00:32:47.760
[Amit Varma]: And as far as redistribution is concerned, you draw the line by saying that you redistribute

00:32:47.760 --> 00:32:53.200
[Amit Varma]: only up to the point that it maximizes sustainable economic growth.

00:32:53.200 --> 00:32:56.840
[Amit Varma]: Doesn't this sort of run up against Kant's categorical imperative that you should not

00:32:56.840 --> 00:33:01.460
[Amit Varma]: use people as a means to an end, where here you are kind of thinking of people as a means

00:33:01.460 --> 00:33:05.720
[Amit Varma]: to an end, which is sustainable economic growth for the future to benefit future generations

00:33:05.720 --> 00:33:06.960
[Guest]: and so on?

00:33:06.960 --> 00:33:09.280
[Guest]: I don't agree with Kant's imperative.

00:33:09.280 --> 00:33:15.380
[Guest]: I think we need to be consequentialists and do things to maximize how good consequences

00:33:15.380 --> 00:33:16.380
[Guest]: will be.

00:33:16.380 --> 00:33:20.800
[Guest]: This will often mean in the short run, some people either lose out or they are treated

00:33:20.800 --> 00:33:22.120
[Guest]: as means to an end.

00:33:22.120 --> 00:33:26.480
[Guest]: But again, if you think of compounded growth over time, you'll have to meet what is by

00:33:26.480 --> 00:33:28.760
[Guest]: far the best outcome.

00:33:28.760 --> 00:33:30.160
[Guest]: So this is not a Kantian book.

00:33:30.160 --> 00:33:33.080
[Guest]: You can think of it in part as a response to Kant.

00:33:33.080 --> 00:33:38.240
[Amit Varma]: And a common criticism against consequentialism, which you also addressed in this book is obviously

00:33:38.240 --> 00:33:43.580
[Amit Varma]: the epistemic problem that, okay, we judge actions according to their consequences.

00:33:43.580 --> 00:33:47.200
[Amit Varma]: But how can we know ahead of time what those consequences will be?

00:33:47.200 --> 00:33:53.080
[Amit Varma]: And this becomes particularly acute at scale at a level of public policy, where we've already

00:33:53.080 --> 00:33:57.640
[Amit Varma]: had enormous follies earlier in the century in terms of central planning and so on, running

00:33:57.640 --> 00:34:00.000
[Amit Varma]: up against Hayek's knowledge problem.

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:06.040
[Amit Varma]: How do you reconcile the epistemic problem that is inevitable when it comes to planning

00:34:06.040 --> 00:34:07.040
[Amit Varma]: anything?

00:34:07.040 --> 00:34:08.040
[Guest]: I mean,

00:34:08.040 --> 00:34:10.500
[Guest]: Well, I think we should bite that bullet and swallow it.

00:34:10.500 --> 00:34:16.440
[Guest]: So in many cases, we should be very modest about how likely we are to be right.

00:34:16.440 --> 00:34:21.300
[Guest]: Of course, you should pursue the course of action you think is most likely to be right.

00:34:21.300 --> 00:34:25.360
[Guest]: But you should not be very dogmatic and think, well, I have it exactly right.

00:34:25.360 --> 00:34:29.560
[Guest]: I would say when it comes to economic growth, we often know a great deal about how to thwart

00:34:29.560 --> 00:34:30.560
[Guest]: it.

00:34:30.560 --> 00:34:34.360
[Guest]: But it's much harder to have very exact knowledge on how to stimulate it.

00:34:34.360 --> 00:34:37.280
[Guest]: And I think that's the level of agnosticism we should have.

00:34:37.280 --> 00:34:41.800
[Guest]: So we shouldn't think we know everything about every public policy issue, because we don't.

00:34:41.800 --> 00:34:43.840
[Amit Varma]: So for me, that's a feature, not a bug.

00:34:43.840 --> 00:34:49.200
[Amit Varma]: Yes, I was, I had an interesting conversation yesterday, I had a historian called Gyan Prakash

00:34:49.200 --> 00:34:55.440
[Amit Varma]: on my show, and he's just written a book about the revisiting the emergency and looking deeper

00:34:55.440 --> 00:34:57.440
[Amit Varma]: into its root causes and all that.

00:34:57.440 --> 00:35:02.880
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that he tangentially wrote about there was the thrust towards family

00:35:02.880 --> 00:35:07.360
[Amit Varma]: planning and population control in India, which, you know, took place over a period

00:35:07.360 --> 00:35:12.800
[Amit Varma]: of decades and was driven by Americans like American institutions like the Ford Foundation,

00:35:12.800 --> 00:35:15.500
[Amit Varma]: were actively talking about coercive family planning.

00:35:15.500 --> 00:35:21.380
[Amit Varma]: And at one point, the American government itself made aid conditional upon the Indian

00:35:21.380 --> 00:35:23.960
[Amit Varma]: government carrying out family planning policies.

00:35:23.960 --> 00:35:27.280
[Amit Varma]: And of course, this was magnified massively during the emergency.

00:35:27.280 --> 00:35:31.920
[Amit Varma]: But leaving that aside, coercive family planning continues to this day, and is based as I know

00:35:31.920 --> 00:35:36.560
[Amit Varma]: you would agree with me on, you know, flawed Malthusian principles and, you know, looking

00:35:36.560 --> 00:35:42.880
[Amit Varma]: at human beings, not as resources, which they are, but as a problem and the damage that

00:35:42.880 --> 00:35:47.760
[Amit Varma]: this sort of thinking caused, at that time was, you know, had enormous consequences.

00:35:47.760 --> 00:35:50.960
[Amit Varma]: I mean, there are millions of people who would have been born and would have lived fulfilling

00:35:50.960 --> 00:35:53.080
[Amit Varma]: lives who simply don't exist.

00:35:53.080 --> 00:35:57.240
[Amit Varma]: And that seemed to me, you know, since it just happened yesterday, it seemed to me to

00:35:57.240 --> 00:36:02.840
[Amit Varma]: be a great example of how, you know, consequentialism can go dramatically wrong, because all of

00:36:02.840 --> 00:36:05.680
[Amit Varma]: those people were acting out of good intentions.

00:36:05.680 --> 00:36:07.200
[Amit Varma]: And they were convinced they were right.

00:36:07.200 --> 00:36:11.440
[Amit Varma]: And that this was a reasonable thing to do for the sake of future generations.

00:36:11.440 --> 00:36:12.920
[Guest]: I agree with all your points.

00:36:12.920 --> 00:36:17.920
[Guest]: But I wouldn't blame consequentialism, I would blame arrogance, a consistent consequentialist

00:36:17.920 --> 00:36:22.120
[Guest]: will recognize how hard it is to calculate consequences.

00:36:22.120 --> 00:36:26.000
[Guest]: And one simple consequence is if you have fewer children, there's less social insurance

00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:31.160
[Guest]: within the family, or, you know, less chance you'll give birth to the next genius or great

00:36:31.160 --> 00:36:32.240
[Guest]: inventor.

00:36:32.240 --> 00:36:33.600
[Guest]: And that's a consequence too.

00:36:33.600 --> 00:36:36.120
[Amit Varma]: So I would say they were not consequentialist enough.

00:36:36.120 --> 00:36:42.320
[Amit Varma]: Right, and, you know, the other sort of criticism that can be leveled against, you know, the

00:36:42.320 --> 00:36:47.160
[Amit Varma]: thesis that you've laid out, is that in your book, you really take the point of view of

00:36:47.160 --> 00:36:53.240
[Amit Varma]: the species or the civilization across this great span of time, and not specifically the

00:36:53.240 --> 00:36:57.280
[Amit Varma]: individual, like, you know, just going back to your earlier quote, when you talk about,

00:36:57.280 --> 00:37:02.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, Cleopatra wanting an extra helping of desert and someone dying of cancer today,

00:37:02.800 --> 00:37:08.200
[Amit Varma]: but the thing is, does someone have the right to tell Cleopatra today to not have an extra

00:37:08.200 --> 00:37:12.000
[Amit Varma]: helping of desert because someone hundreds of years later may die of cancer?

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:17.760
[Guest]: Well, you have to ask which are the actions of Cleopatra that might have wrecked the world.

00:37:17.760 --> 00:37:22.440
[Guest]: And maybe there were some she was not in every way a good ruler, as I understand it.

00:37:22.440 --> 00:37:25.480
[Guest]: But I don't think her heapings of desert were the problem.

00:37:25.480 --> 00:37:28.400
[Guest]: That's the kind of joke that sentence.

00:37:28.400 --> 00:37:34.480
[Guest]: She did not invest in durable institutions that could be passed down along the generations.

00:37:34.480 --> 00:37:38.680
[Guest]: And for that, I think we should condemn her and she should have done it.

00:37:38.680 --> 00:37:44.160
[Guest]: So this idea that there's a cultural persistence to good institutions, I think that's the obligation

00:37:44.160 --> 00:37:46.640
[Guest]: of leaders is to support good institutions.

00:37:46.640 --> 00:37:47.640
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough.

00:37:47.640 --> 00:37:51.840
[Amit Varma]: I'll quote another sentence from you where you sort of you handle the epistemic problem

00:37:51.840 --> 00:37:58.000
[Amit Varma]: and you talk about how, when it comes to small uncertainties, we should just default to respecting

00:37:58.000 --> 00:37:59.080
[Amit Varma]: rights.

00:37:59.080 --> 00:38:03.920
[Amit Varma]: But when it comes to, you know, clearly big consequences, like sustained economic growth

00:38:03.920 --> 00:38:08.640
[Amit Varma]: way into the future or preserving the environment for future generations, then we should act

00:38:08.640 --> 00:38:10.200
[Amit Varma]: decisively.

00:38:10.200 --> 00:38:15.080
[Amit Varma]: And you know, you spoke about not being paralyzed by epistemic uncertainty.

00:38:15.080 --> 00:38:19.960
[Amit Varma]: So there's a sentence where you say, quote, rather than letting it paralyze us, we can

00:38:19.960 --> 00:38:26.180
[Amit Varma]: think of radical uncertainty as giving us the freedom to act morally, stop quote.

00:38:26.180 --> 00:38:30.960
[Amit Varma]: And my thought here was, you know, why do we need radical uncertainty to give us the

00:38:30.960 --> 00:38:32.600
[Amit Varma]: freedom to act morally?

00:38:32.600 --> 00:38:35.120
[Amit Varma]: Why not act morally anyway?

00:38:35.120 --> 00:38:37.520
[Amit Varma]: And wouldn't that lead to the best consequences?

00:38:37.520 --> 00:38:41.240
[Guest]: Well, I think maybe it's easier to act morally.

00:38:41.240 --> 00:38:45.800
[Guest]: If you're not sure your rights infringement will lead to good practical benefits.

00:38:45.800 --> 00:38:50.720
[Guest]: So take this course of family planning, something I would be opposed to.

00:38:50.720 --> 00:38:54.520
[Guest]: People really should have thought twice, three times about this and said, you know, we really

00:38:54.520 --> 00:38:57.620
[Guest]: don't even know if this will do good.

00:38:57.620 --> 00:39:01.160
[Guest]: And if you don't even know that you ought to think it will do good.

00:39:01.160 --> 00:39:03.840
[Guest]: I think it's much easier to say, well, look, this is wrong.

00:39:03.840 --> 00:39:05.420
[Guest]: It's coercing people.

00:39:05.420 --> 00:39:08.200
[Guest]: We just shouldn't do it and leave it aside.

00:39:08.200 --> 00:39:13.420
[Guest]: So I think it opens up the space to be moral without always looking over your shoulder

00:39:13.420 --> 00:39:18.480
[Guest]: and wondering who's going to lose as a result of this.

00:39:18.480 --> 00:39:19.480
[Guest]: Who's going to die?

00:39:19.480 --> 00:39:22.080
[Guest]: What other grave consequences am I creating?

00:39:22.080 --> 00:39:25.040
[Guest]: In a lot of cases, you just don't know, so do the right thing.

00:39:25.040 --> 00:39:29.300
[Amit Varma]: So tell me if I've sort of summarized the thesis of your book accurately.

00:39:29.300 --> 00:39:34.320
[Amit Varma]: You write that we have to think consequentially and we have to use rights as a constraint

00:39:34.320 --> 00:39:35.460
[Amit Varma]: for that.

00:39:35.460 --> 00:39:40.000
[Amit Varma]: And we have to most importantly, balance the lives of future generations and consider them

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:41.760
[Amit Varma]: as important as ours.

00:39:41.760 --> 00:39:46.680
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, we have to aim for sustainable economic growth, pointing out, you know, the

00:39:46.680 --> 00:39:50.920
[Amit Varma]: principle of compound interest, which philosophers may not have paid as much attention to as

00:39:50.920 --> 00:39:52.320
[Amit Varma]: accountants.

00:39:52.320 --> 00:39:58.320
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, what you prescribe is that let us always aim for sustainable economic

00:39:58.320 --> 00:40:01.880
[Amit Varma]: growth using rights as a constraint.

00:40:01.880 --> 00:40:04.600
[Amit Varma]: And that's essentially the thesis of your book.

00:40:04.600 --> 00:40:06.760
[Guest]: Is that an accurate summation?

00:40:06.760 --> 00:40:08.240
[Guest]: I agree with all that.

00:40:08.240 --> 00:40:14.360
[Amit Varma]: I'm never sure that a summation of a book is possible, but what you said sounded great.

00:40:14.360 --> 00:40:16.360
[Amit Varma]: And is your thinking sort of a work in progress?

00:40:16.360 --> 00:40:19.640
[Amit Varma]: Like, did you think differently 10 years ago or 20 years ago?

00:40:19.640 --> 00:40:24.680
[Amit Varma]: And if so, what changed over a period of time as you thought about the book?

00:40:24.680 --> 00:40:30.780
[Guest]: I think I've tried to improve the ideas, but I don't think they've changed fundamentally.

00:40:30.780 --> 00:40:36.360
[Guest]: Maybe the main change in the book over time was the earlier drafts had a lot more on sustainability

00:40:36.360 --> 00:40:40.840
[Guest]: and preserving the value of civilization against existential risk.

00:40:40.840 --> 00:40:45.720
[Guest]: I haven't at all repudiated those ideas, but I found they've come out in a lot of other

00:40:45.720 --> 00:40:46.720
[Guest]: books.

00:40:46.720 --> 00:40:52.120
[Guest]: And I ended up mostly taking them out of mine just because I wanted to focus on what I thought

00:40:52.120 --> 00:40:53.880
[Guest]: was my unique contribution.

00:40:53.880 --> 00:40:55.880
[Amit Varma]: That would be the biggest change.

00:40:55.880 --> 00:41:00.400
[Amit Varma]: And sort of moving away from the book for a moment, you know, you sort of live in America

00:41:00.400 --> 00:41:05.220
[Amit Varma]: in the age of Trump and just looking at the way things are going, for example, you speak

00:41:05.220 --> 00:41:09.520
[Amit Varma]: about how things might seem to be going backwards in the US, but they are doing well in the

00:41:09.520 --> 00:41:10.520
[Amit Varma]: rest of the world.

00:41:10.520 --> 00:41:15.520
[Amit Varma]: But Trump has just engaged on what could be called negative, some trade wars with China

00:41:15.520 --> 00:41:22.160
[Amit Varma]: and others, which actually have a negative impact on the entire world, including us in

00:41:22.160 --> 00:41:24.960
[Amit Varma]: India and increased instability everywhere.

00:41:24.960 --> 00:41:27.760
[Amit Varma]: Do you feel more hopeful about the future?

00:41:27.760 --> 00:41:30.280
[Guest]: How do you look at all of that?

00:41:30.280 --> 00:41:35.640
[Guest]: I think the world today is in a positive place that I could not have imagined, say, 40 years

00:41:35.640 --> 00:41:36.640
[Guest]: ago.

00:41:36.640 --> 00:41:39.040
[Guest]: And that should make us quite optimistic.

00:41:39.040 --> 00:41:46.360
[Guest]: But I do see a number of countries, including in Eastern and Central Europe, Brazil, some

00:41:46.360 --> 00:41:51.160
[Guest]: features of government in the United States, some features of government in India, China

00:41:51.160 --> 00:41:55.040
[Guest]: being more autocratic, which I think are getting worse.

00:41:55.040 --> 00:41:56.640
[Guest]: And that scares me.

00:41:56.640 --> 00:42:01.360
[Guest]: So I would say the last two or three years, we've maybe needed to reassess our optimism

00:42:01.360 --> 00:42:02.360
[Guest]: a bit.

00:42:02.360 --> 00:42:07.040
[Guest]: But I still see the optimistic trends as stronger than the bad politics.

00:42:07.040 --> 00:42:08.840
[Guest]: And I think the US will survive Trump.

00:42:08.840 --> 00:42:11.520
[Guest]: I don't agree with the trade war.

00:42:11.520 --> 00:42:17.440
[Guest]: But I do think China was doing a lot to steal intellectual property and conduct espionage.

00:42:17.440 --> 00:42:19.520
[Guest]: And we did need to poke back at them in some way.

00:42:19.520 --> 00:42:21.960
[Guest]: I don't agree with what we did.

00:42:21.960 --> 00:42:26.280
[Guest]: But I think Trump, in some ways, has been speaking the truth about China also.

00:42:26.280 --> 00:42:31.640
[Amit Varma]: And also, do you think that your moral vision for the future is something that or any moral

00:42:31.640 --> 00:42:34.920
[Amit Varma]: vision for the future can really percolate to the level of politics?

00:42:34.920 --> 00:42:39.240
[Amit Varma]: Because maybe I'm biased by the politics that I see in India, but what I see here is that

00:42:39.240 --> 00:42:44.520
[Amit Varma]: politics tends to be morally corrosive, that once people enter the political sphere, the

00:42:44.520 --> 00:42:46.640
[Amit Varma]: lust for power drowns out everything else.

00:42:46.640 --> 00:42:52.880
[Amit Varma]: And even if they went into it with good intentions, and, you know, specific moral visions, those

00:42:52.880 --> 00:42:58.200
[Amit Varma]: disappear as the imperatives of that political game kind of play out, and it becomes sort

00:42:58.200 --> 00:43:03.520
[Amit Varma]: of impossible for anyone to really have any principles apart from catering to the interest

00:43:03.520 --> 00:43:09.000
[Amit Varma]: groups and getting reelected once they reach the higher levels of politics.

00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:13.480
[Guest]: You've had very clear moments in the history of Indian politics where people did the right

00:43:13.480 --> 00:43:21.480
[Guest]: thing, people who fought for independence from the United Kingdom, Ambedkar, the reforms

00:43:21.480 --> 00:43:23.160
[Guest]: of the 1990s.

00:43:23.160 --> 00:43:28.480
[Guest]: I'm not saying those sentiments always last forever, but people have stood up and acted

00:43:28.480 --> 00:43:34.120
[Guest]: for right and had lasting impact, and also boosted the rate of economic growth in India,

00:43:34.120 --> 00:43:37.560
[Guest]: which is much higher than it used to be.

00:43:37.560 --> 00:43:43.120
[Guest]: And post-independence was much higher than that compared to being a colony of Great Britain.

00:43:43.120 --> 00:43:47.520
[Guest]: So even in Indian history, which has, you know, been fraught with a lot of negative

00:43:47.520 --> 00:43:50.080
[Guest]: events, we've seen this happen and succeed.

00:43:50.080 --> 00:43:52.880
[Guest]: So I would again be more optimistic than not.

00:43:52.880 --> 00:43:55.160
[Amit Varma]: Tyler, let's end on a hopeful note.

00:43:55.160 --> 00:43:58.120
[Amit Varma]: Thanks a lot for spending so much of your time talking to me.

00:43:58.120 --> 00:43:59.120
[Guest]: My pleasure.

00:43:59.120 --> 00:44:02.400
[Guest]: And thank you for your interest in my book and for reading it so carefully.

00:44:02.400 --> 00:44:05.400
[Guest]: Thanks, Ryla.

00:44:05.400 --> 00:44:10.240
[Amit Varma]: Like every good book should be, Stubborn Attachments is thought-provoking, and it's also short

00:44:10.240 --> 00:44:14.960
[Amit Varma]: enough to be read entirely in one sitting, so I strongly recommend that you pick it up.

00:44:14.960 --> 00:44:18.800
[Amit Varma]: Because it's so accessible, it might even be a gateway book for new readers interested

00:44:18.800 --> 00:44:20.240
[Amit Varma]: in moral philosophy.

